1 introduction

ggplot .

(mapping) data (, , ) (, , bar).
statistical transformations.
data ( mapping ) . -data .
-mapping :

  1. layer - geometric elements and statistical transformations. geometrics like - points, lines and polygons. Statistical transformations that summarize the data.
    Every plot has at least one layer which describes how to render each observation.

  2. scales - a mapping from the data space to the aesthetic space - what we see in the color, shape,size, and legend.(what makespossible to read the original data values from the plot)

  3. coordinate system - how data coordinates are mapped to the plane of the graphic - axes and gridlines. (we will use only Cartesian coordinate system)

  4. facet - break up and display subsets of data.

  5. theme - finer points of display, like the font size and background colour.

    x = "City mileage/gallon",

labelled

: , legend , , .

styled <- labelled +
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12),
    legend.background = element_rect(fill = "white", size = 4, colour = "white"),
    legend.justification = c(0, 1),
    legend.position = c(0, 1),
    axis.ticks = element_line(colour = "grey70", size = 0.2),
    panel.grid.major = element_line(colour = "grey70", size = 0.2),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  )

:

base_t <- base + labs(title = "This is a ggplot") + xlab(NULL) + ylab(NULL)

p1 <- base_t + theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", colour = "red", hjust = 1, size = 16))

p2 <- base_t + theme(plot.title = element_text(margin = margin(t = 10, b = 10)))

p3 <- base_t + theme(panel.grid.major = element_line(size = 2, linetype = "dotted", color = "purple"))

p4 <- base_t +  theme(panel.grid.minor = element_blank())

p1 + p2 + p3 + p4

values <- seq(from = -2, to = 2, by = .01)

df <- data.frame(x = values, y = values ^ 3)

ggplot(df, aes(x, y)) + 
  geom_path() + 
  labs(y = quote(f(x) == x^3),
       title = "first line \nsecond line")
